00:04:13.000 --> 00:04:17.000
So, like, opening statements, like, yeah, Libby said it very well.

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:24.000
Like, I think, I don't know, 10, 20 years ago, most websites or a lot of websites rendered server side, right?

00:04:24.000 --> 00:04:31.000
They would do a bunch of stuff on the server and then the server and then your computer would retrieve a HTML table or whatever from the server.

00:04:31.000 --> 00:04:33.000
And that's when you could scrape that with Beautiful Soup, right?

00:04:33.000 --> 00:04:37.000
You can do a request.get or HTR and R.

00:04:37.000 --> 00:04:38.000
My R is very good.

00:04:38.000 --> 00:04:39.000
I haven't used R in ages.

00:04:39.000 --> 00:04:45.000
But you can basically pull that in and then you've got this basically giant string of HTML and various tools like Beautiful Soup

00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:50.000
or other things can parse those tables and extract the data, right?

00:04:50.000 --> 00:04:55.000
I don't know when the trend started, but now a lot of times what happens is the server is not sending you HTML.

00:04:55.000 --> 00:04:57.000
The server is sending you data.

00:04:57.000 --> 00:05:01.000
And JavaScript running on your computer is taking that data and building the pieces of the website for you.

00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:10.000
So the table you see on a website is not, if you went and, like, curled that from the command line or if you request.get or whatever,

00:05:10.000 --> 00:05:16.000
programmatically with some retrieval code that does not process JavaScript,

00:05:16.000 --> 00:05:20.000
you would just get a bunch of JavaScript tags and you wouldn't actually have a table, right?

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:22.000
So there's two reasons to do these private APIs.

00:05:22.000 --> 00:05:26.000
One is because, like, it's cleaner and better than trying to do Beautiful Soup.

00:05:26.000 --> 00:05:29.000
And two is sometimes Beautiful Soup won't work, right?

00:05:29.000 --> 00:05:34.000
Because, like, unless you'd have to, like, maybe save the source from a web browser or something to kind of get that generated table.

